fields.title: Ceiling Repairs
fields.description: Flood revision. Ceiling is coming in after the heavy rains. Please rectify.
fields.scope:
Internal and external repairs to building 150 to fix water ingress and damage.

Internal Scope
ò Place protective floor covering
ò Disconnect lights and exit sign
ò Remove existing ceiling
ò De nail existing rafters
ò Place new shadow mould
ò Place new 13mm plasterboard
ò Sand seal and paint including walls
ò Replace lights and exit sign

External
The ridge, rafters and battens have failed at redirecting water off the roof, causing water to enter
directly into the roof space and cause damage to the ceiling. Upon inspection it was also noted that
there have been many attempts to seal the leaks.
Aurify proposes to construct an additional roof over the existing, leaving enough roof for access to
the communication and electrical services. This will be achieved by an extended barge flashing that
can be removed at a later stage should the services need to be reached.

Scope
ò Provide security fencing both sides of the project
ò Provide scaffolding both sides of the building with the platform at serviceable height for roof
works
ò Remove barge cappings high side and expose top plate
ò Remove roofing to lower side roofing to lower side to expose same.
ò Place new top plates and dwalf wall on high side, leaving enough room for access to electrical
services place rafters and battens in preparation for roof sheeting
ò Place new roof sheeting using existing gutter
ò Place extended 2-piece barge flashing for future access if required
ò Place side flashings onto new roof and place flashing onto existing roof
ò Remove all scaffolding and debris leave site clean
fields.work_notes:
+ FloodSax ordered and delivered to Glenbrook ($2640 + 10%)

21-09-22 Progress:
    Inside
    The ceiling was removed, and we were able to Identify several roof sheets that were unsupported 
    Supporting timbers have been placed to lift the roof sheets back into there correct position 

    Outside
    Roof screws tightened and Preliminary sealer Placed to potential leak areas 

    Next stage 
    Roof needs to be Tested  with the ceiling still removed , to observe for any leaks
    (It is Due to Rain in the next coming days }

    If the repair has been successful, another final water proof membrane will be placed over the  preliminary sealer
    And the ceiling will be replaced 

    Note: this Repair has been attempted at request.  to be cost effective

fields.title: Cracking Structure Remediation
fields.description: The RHQ building is badly cracked and is uninhabitable
fields.special_instructions: Heritage classification: High significance. Where work may impact the building fabric, stop and review heritage considerations with BGIS
fields.scope:
Remediation of structural damage for Building 007 as per structural engineers advice

1. Carry out Risk Assessment and Safe Work Method Statement
2. Attend site to consult with POC for required works.
3. Supply all materials, labour and escort for works.
4. Remove all furniture in building and affected areas.
5. Zone off area for duration of works.
6. Set up protection, scaffolding and props.
7. Complete replacement of archways as per engineersÆ recommendations.
8. Helifix 50L/m of crack stitching.
9. Supply and install reclaimed bricks, including sand and cement where relevant.
10. Supply and install internal plastering as recommended.
11. Supply and install heritage plaster as required from heritage.
12. Complete painting of area (150m2 of walls, 25m2 of trims, and 50m2 of ceilings.
13. Disposal of all waste and site clean-up prior to handover.

Preliminaries
ò Remove furniture from affected areas and protect all assets/furniture accordingly.
ò Scaffolding will be set up on stair case to carry out repair work
ò Site to be zoned off for duration of work.
ò Skip bin to be supplied on site for all trades

Plaster, Brickwork & Render Repair Works
ò All plaster repair work to start first.
ò Remove all cracked and drummy plaster in affected areas.
ò Supply and install 6mm Thor helical bars into affected areas which have movement in brickwork (50lm)
ò Render with heritage mix to a screed finish & recess edge where needed. Set plaster to a smooth finish.
ò Remove archway brickwork and supply & fit new arch bars & brick up arch/wall.
ò Supply & fit new arch moulds. Supply & install 6mm Thor helical bars to brickwork Between new & existing render & set in

Drummy plaster & render to be removed and reinstated ôLike for Likeö.
Painting Works
ò Caulking to all hairline cracks to nominated sections and cornices and repainting.
ò Remove, patch and sand all loose flaking paint to ceilings and repaint. These works to be undertaken by painter not plasterer.
ò Minor patching and preparation to walls and repaint in same colour. Painter to undertake some prep.
ò Repainting all nominated walls after plastering / rendering works.

fields.title: Waterproof Repairs
fields.description: The interior of the building is painted with a waterproof membrane. This seems to have failed as there is water pooling in the building. Membrane needs to be repaired or replaced
fields.special_instructions: Heritage classification: High significance. Where work may impact the building fabric, stop and review heritage considerations with BGIS
fields.scope:
Waterproofing works to walls and floor.

Wall Works:
-	Prepare the walls to be waterproofed, remove all previous waterproofing back to brick work, to a clean brick face
-	Hand grinding to walls and heavy machine grinding to floor 
-	All walls to be grinded with vacuum extractors 
-	Carry out minor patching of wall if required 
-	Prepare working area for clean air flow during application of membranes 
-	Apply 2 coats of negative pressure membrane (RM60) (flexible polymer cementitious membrane designed for negative waterproofing application over concrete and masonry surfaces)
-	Paint over membrane with primer & 2 coats (colour TBC)

Note: if walls have lost their structural integrity a reassessment on procedure and costs will have to be done

Floor Works:
-	Grind floor to provide ôkeyö for coating system
-	Supply & install 2 x coats of Hydrepoxy negative pressure treatment (Ardex WPM 300)
-	Supply & install 1 x 2.5mm trowel coat with (30/60) grit (Hychem GPT)
-	Supply & install 1 x .5mm colour coat (colour TBC) (Hychem SF32)

Duration of the works is approx. 2 to 3 weeks including cure time before the floor is trafficable again.

fields.title: Concrete Cancer Repairs
fields.description:
Rectify concrete cancer based at Building 14 RAAF Richmond. 
Include all aspects to be carried out by Aurify. Treatment, access, paints, renders etc
fields.scope:
Concrete Repairs to Building 14 exposed external slab edges under brickwork
Repair Method: 
-	Identify all cracked concrete edges for repair (From visual inspection there is approx. 60 lineal metres of repairs to be carried out across 12 separate concrete faces)
-	Cut out approx. 60 lineal metres of cracked concrete to form a straight line as practical as possible to the good slab face up to the under side of the brick work to a minimum of 5mm to 10mm 
-	Remove concrete in repair area to a minimum of 10mm through to saw cut
-	Clean area of any loose concrete
-	Identify any exposed steel reinforcing & locate any rusted steel
-	Expose rusted steel by removing the immediate concrete around the steel including behind the steel
-	Remove any loose scale & rust & prepare to a bright finish where possible
-	Apply Nitoprime to all exposed steel immediately after steel has been exposed. Recoat if necessary
-	Clean the substrate with water & let it soak in & apply & scrub in Nitobond HAR
-	Once tacky apply Renderoc HB40 or HB70 depending on the depth & type of repair
-	Repair to a flush finish to the existing slab edge face & up to the underside of the brickwork
-	Where necessary after the repairs have been completed where there is no break between the underside of the brick work to the slab a small saw cut is to be carried out for all the nominated areas & sealed with a grey UV resistant polyurethane sealant to aid further cracking due to building movement
-	Where there is gaps between the slab & brickwork remove old sealant & re-apply grey UV resistant polyurethane sealant to reseal as required
-	Clean all surfaces to prepare for painting
-	Painting of Slab Edge
-	Apply Emer Clad Primer to all new repairs & allow to dry
-	Apply 2 coats of Emer Clad Facade to all slab edges (approx. 115 Lineal metres)

fields.title: Heritage Window Repairs
fields.description: Repair and repaint all external windows to the building 27 in total as per GML Heritage report
fields.scope:
- Remove all flaking lead based paint from the exterior side of the windows by wet scraping.
- Carry out all work-safe protocols in relation to the lead remediation works.
- Allow for air-monitoring during the wet scraping process.
- Allow for Hygienist clearance certificate after completion of the wet scraping works.
- Once the wet scraping and lead remediation are completed, the windows are to be fully primed and undercoated with Dulux 3 in 1 oil based undercoat.
- Patch and fill all holes and cracks in timber with appropriate filler.
- Fix and replace all damaged or missing window glazing putty.
- Spot prime all filling and patching with oil based undercoat.
- Apply two finish coats of Dulux Aquanamel gloss acrylic in matching Brunswick Green colour to all exterior windows.
- We propose the works to be carried out off Mechanical Access (Knuckle Booms) equipment.

Exclusions:
- The preparation or painting of the small windows in the Clock Tower.
- Any sample testing for lead in the existing paint coat system.
- Any sample testing of the glazing putty for Asbestos.
- Any carpentry repairs or timber maintenance repairs that are required to the windows, ie, Replacement of rotten or damaged timber sills etc.
- Any scaffold hire or erection of scaffold as we are using mechanical access equipment.
- Any repairs or damage to the grass / lawn at the front of the building.
- Any preparation or painting works to any exterior doors or frames.
- Any preparation or painting works to any other previously painted exterior surfaces apart from the windows.

ò Implement and install an eco-friendly, sustainable backyard play ground including the use of rocks and pine bark in the garden beds, in addition to the inclusion of native and bush tucker plants that promotes and creates a sensory friendly play space to support children with additional needs.
ò Bush tucker garden, native plants, and yarning circle promote a culturally safe space for Indigenous children and encourages children to learn about Country, growing their own food, respecting nature, learning about nutrition and healthy eating etc. This also supports and welcomes native wildlife into the space. Native gardens consume less water for maintenance. Foods grown in this space to be used in the menu which will in-turn reduce costs for food related purchases. Great opportunity for us to establish relationships with our local Indigenous community.
ò Water tank and clothesline promote sustainability:
ò Pergola with decking to provide much needed shade cover, along with a flat and safe surface where learning experiences can be established for children with mobility issues. This is also a great æquietÆ area in the outdoor space to support children with additional needs and sensory processing issues. Hanging plants to be used to help create a cooling effect during warmer months."

fields.inspection_notes:
Innovation install Vent a roof system and repair roof sheets
ò Upon our inspection we could see that the internal roof space has a lot of humidity and condensation, due to no ventilators being installed and also the fibreglass insulation not being thick enough with the roof razors which leaves a 70mm air pocket that builds condensation every morning.
ò From here our team recommends that the roof sheets be removed 2 sheets at a time and new R1.5 55mm Insulation be installed over the roof razors to remove the 70mm ait pocket that was left previously. The two sheets that were removed will be refixed and then the next two will be removed and the same process will continue until the whole roof is complete.
ò During this inspection we measured the internal ceiling height, width and length to calculate the internal roof volume.
These measurements will be cross referenced with our ventilation professional to apply the best products to rectify the problem in the cinema ceiling space.
ò Our team calculated in total 1010m3
ò Due to the building being a cinema and the amount of heat can be generated from this we recommend that the ceiling space have 12 air changes per hour. Which means the air volume in this space will be replaced 12 times.
ò To execute works scaffolding will be set-up around the entire perimeter of the cinema for tradesman to access the roof and materials handling.
ò Our team suggests installing 3 Hybrid Backward Curved Centrifugal ventilatorÆs. Which is capable of producing 12.72 air changes per hour.
ò These ventilatorÆs have their own electric motors with humidity and temperature sensors. These sensors will be set and the ventilatorÆs will turn on when too hot or humid.
ò These ventilatorÆs are more superior than your typical whirly birds that rely on wind to spin the whirly bird and extract heat.
ò To achieve these air changes, we will also need make up air. So open air to be able to be passed through the roof, into the ceiling space and then extracted through the newly installed ventilators.
ò For the 3 ventilatorÆs installed we need 0.9m2 on the roof to be opened to let air pass.
ò Our team suggest opening 4 four 500mmX 500m cut outs on four corners of roof near the gutter.
ò These holes then will have four gooseneck vents installed with back tray flashing to the ridge capping to render them watertight.
ò Fresh air will flow through these vents, into the ceiling space and extracted by the ventilatorÆs.
ò Once complete our team will remove the ridge capping and install the newly released innovative Vent-a-roof system.
Our team also suggest installing this product to work in conjunction with the ventilatorÆs.
ò This system works with the natural hot air rising and being vented through this system naturally. This will also take pressure off the ventilatorÆs from switching on all the time. This system also comes with its own new colorbond ridge capping system.
ò Warranty and Certificates for all colorbond products, ventilatorÆs and Vent-a-roof system will be supplied.
ò Before and after air quality tests will be taken to check and analyse the difference in heat and humidity.
ò Installation of electrical component to allow for connection to motor driven ventilators.

This results in only one sub-contractor, in-turn reducing the costs and margins from several sub-contractors/vendors (e.g. floor grinding machine & operator, epoxy purchase, and epoxy application).

Preparing and repainting the flooring of Hanger 307 in an epoxy coating.

Option 1 - Clear Polyurethane Finish (Recommended for durability & Cost)
ò Install 1 x temporary 3 phase 32 Amp outlet to power 3 phase floor grinder
ò Remove vinyl from 2 small rooms and carpet from larger room

ò Application of Self Priming ôclearö Polyurethane (Hychem PU100) to the Main Hanger and 4 nominated adjacent rooms
Note Slab transitions will be minimised through the grinding process.

Option 2 - Colour 2-part Epoxy Finish
ò Install 1 x temporary 3 phase 32 Amp outlet to power 3 phase floor grinder
ò Remove vinyl from 2 small rooms and carpet from larger room
ò Undertake surface preparation to 4 nominated adjacent rooms & main hanger floor via surface grinding to achieve product key
ò Application of Self Priming ôclearö Polyurethane (E100) to the Main Hanger and 4 nominated adjacent rooms
ò Application of 2 x colour coats in 2 part epoxy (SF20FG in any colour)
Note Slab transitions will be minimised through the grinding process

Option 3 - 2-part Epoxy/ Clear Polyurethane Finish

ò High pressure clean

fields.title: Flood Repairs
fields.description:
Heavy rainfall from a storm event FEB 2023 caused gutter blockage resulting in internal water ingress and flooding, with extensive damage to ceiling/wall lining and flooring in mezzanine office accommodation.

*NB, HVAC FCU equipment is located above mezzanine offices that will need to be temporarily relocated during ceiling repairs.
- Mezzanine roof inside hangar has no fall protection where it has been recommended to have temporary handrail system in place during works.

1: Temp handrail system to be to be installed where recommendations have been made by using 200x200x200 safety barrier base's, 90mm timber post and 70x35H2 timbers as rails.

2. Remove damaged/water logged plywood flooring from mezzanine and replace. Like for like.

3. Move all office furnishings out of current office in to adjacent office.

4. Disconnect electrical fittings/lights from internal lining where water damage has occurred.

5. Remove approx. 30m2 of internal gyprock & 90mm cove cornice.

6. Supply and install new 10mm gyprock and 90mm cove cornice.

7. Paint all new works. 1 coat primer and 2 coats of ceiling white.

8. Replace water damaged carpet inside affected office with new. Colour to me matched as close as possible - Approximately 32m2.

9. Replace approximately 24m2 of vinyl within the corridor using slimline joining strips - Colour to me matched as close as possible.

10. Remove all rubbish/materials from site.


Proposed HVAC Scope of Works:

- Access units, isolate and tag out power supply.

- Reclaim all refrigerant into pump down bottle.

- Disconnect pipe work, electrics and drain from FCU and seal up pipe work to prevent non condensables entering the system.

- Move FCU away from area of roof that the building team will be working on.

- Once building team has finished roof repairs, move evaporator back into place.

- Reconnect pipework electrics and drain.

- Pressure test and evacuate refrigeration pipework.

- Charge system with refrigerant.

- Check and monitor unit operations and refrigerant charge.
